=== Example 46 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.

All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

Combining these premises, we can see that Cristiano Ronaldo is not a top soccer player because he cannot use his left foot very efficiently. Therefore, the conclusion "Cristiano Ronaldo is not a top soccer player" follows from the given premises.

All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.

</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

A first-order logic sentence is correct if the sentence can be proved true.
A first-order logic sentence is incorrect if the sentence can be proved false.
A first-order logic sentence is uncertain if the sentence cannot be proved true or false.

<CONCLUSION>
The conclusion is not uncertain.

=== Example 49 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

For example, the first set of premises includes:

1. All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
2. All woodware is biodegradable.
3. All paper is woodware.
4. Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
5. All environment-friendly things are good.
6. A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

We can translate these premises into FOL expressions as follows:

1. ∀x (Biodegradable(x) → Environment-Friendly(x))
2. ∀x (Woodware(x) → Biodegradable(x))
3. ∀x (Paper(x) → Woodware(x))
4. ¬ ∃x (Good(x) & Bad(x))
5. ∀x (Environment-Friendly(x) → Good(x))
6. ∃x (Paper(x) ∨ Environment-Friendly(x))

Given the conclusion:

A worksheet is not biodegradable.

We can evaluate the validity of the argument by checking if the conclusion follows logically from the premises. In this case, we can use the law of excluded middle to prove that the conclusion is true:

1. Assume that a worksheet is biodegradable. Then, by the law of excluded middle, it is either environment-friendly or not environment-friendly. However, we know that all environment-friendly things are good, so if the worksheet is environment-friendly, it is good. But we also know that nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing, so the worksheet cannot be good. Therefore, the worksheet must be not environment-friendly.
2. Since the worksheet is not environment-friendly, it is not biodegradable. Therefore, the conclusion follows logically from the premises.

In this case, the conclusion is true.

</CONCLUSION>

If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.

</EVALUATE>

Generation 6:
Let's analyze the given logical problem step by step. First, we will translate each of the given premises into FOL expressions.

Premise 1: All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
Lemma: Biodegradable(x) → Environment-friendly(x)

Premise 2: All woodware is biodegradable.
Lemma: Woodware(x) → Biodegradable(x)

Premise 3: All paper is woodware.
Lemma: Paper(x) → Woodware(x)

Premise 4: Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
Lemma: Good(x) ∧ Bad(x) → ¬Good(x) ∧ ¬Bad(x)

Premise 5: All environment-friendly things are good.
Lemma: Environment-friendly(x) → Good(x)

Premise 6: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
Lemma: Worksheet(x) → Paper(x) ∨ Environment-friendly(x)

Premise 7: A worksheet is biodegradable if and only if it is environment-friendly.
Lemma: Biodegradable(x) ↔ Environment-friendly(x)

Premise 8: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Lemma: Real Madrid(x) → La Liga(x) ∧ Barcelona(x) → La Liga(x)

Premise 9: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Lemma: Received-points(Real Madrid, Barcelona) → Real Madrid > Barcelona

Premise 10: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
Lemma: Received-points(Real Madrid, Barcelona) → Received-points(Barcelona, Real Madrid) ∧ Received-points(Barcelona, Real Madrid) → Received-points(Real Madrid, Barcelona)

Premise 11: Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
Lemma: Spends-most-time-on-sports(Amy) → Olympic-gold-medal-winner(Amy)

Premise 12: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is not a Nobel laureate.
Lemma: Not-Olympic-gold-medal-winner(Amy) → Not-Nobel-laureate(Amy)

Premise 13: Everyone who works for a government department pays a tax on their salary.
Lemma: Government-department(x) → Pays-tax(x)

Premise 14: Everyone in the army is an employee of a government department.
Lemma: Army(x) → Government-department(x)

Premise 15: Everyone convicted of murder goes to prison.
Lemma: Convicted-of-murder(x) → Goes-to-prison(x)

Premise 16: Everyone who has been to prison has a criminal record.
Lemma: Goes-to-prison(x) → Criminal-record(x)

Premise 17: James was either once convicted of murder, or spent time in prison.
Lemma: Convicted-of-murder(x) → Spent-time-in-prison(x) ∨ Spent-time-in-prison(x) → Convicted-of-murder(x)

Premise 18: James either has a criminal record, or pays his taxes.
Lemma: Criminal-record(x) → ¬Pays-taxes(x) ∨ Pays-taxes(x) → Criminal-record(x)

Premise 19: If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate.
Lemma: Not-Olympic-gold-medal-winner(Amy) → Nobel-laureate(Amy)

Premise 20: Inception is a sci-fi movie.
Lemma: Inception(x) → Sci-fi(x)

Premise 21: Mac is neither a folk song nor a sci-fi movie.
Lemma: Not-folk-song(Mac) → Not-sci-fi(Mac)

Premise 22: If someone can make cookies and muffins, they are a baker.
Lemma: Can-make-cookies-and-muffins(x) → Baker(x)

Premise 23: Bakers who can also make scrambled eggs can make a good breakfast.
Lemma: Baker(x) ∧ Can-make-scrambled-eggs(x) → Can-make-good-breakfast(x)

Premise 24: Luke can make cookies, scrambled eggs, and muffins, but not pasta.
Lemma: Can-make-cookies(Luke) ∧ Can-make-scrambled-eggs(Luke) ∧ Can-make-muffins(Luke) ∧ ¬Can-make-pasta(Luke)

Premise 25: Luke is a chef.
Lemma: Can-make-good-breakfast(Luke) → Chef(Luke)

Premise 26: ETS develops various standardized tests primarily in the United States for K-12 and higher education.
Lemma: Develops-tests(ETS, K-12, higher-education, United States) → True

Premise 27: ETS administers international tests, including the TOEFL, TOEIC, GRE, and subject tests.
Lemma: Administers-tests(ETS, international, TOEFL, TOEIC, GRE, subject tests, etc.) → True

Premise 28: Many of the assessments ETS develops are associated with entry to the US tertiary and quaternary education institutions.
Lemma: Associated-with-entry-to-US-tertiary-and-quaternary-education-institutions(ETS, assessments) → True

Premise 29: ETS also develops K-12 statewide assessments used for accountability testing in many states.
Lemma: Develops-assessments(ETS, K-12, statewide, accountability, many states) → True

<EVALUATE>

The problem asks whether a conclusion follows from the given premises. Based on the premises, the conclusion is "A worksheet is not biodegradable". We will evaluate whether this conclusion follows from the premises using the rules of inference.

First, we will use the law of excluded middle to show that there are two cases to consider: either a worksheet is biodegradable or it is not biodegradable.

1. Premise 6: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
2. Rule of excluded middle: A worksheet is either biodegradable or not biodegradable.
3. Premise 7: Biodegradable(x) ↔ Environment-friendly(x)
4. Rule of excluded middle: A worksheet is either environment-friendly or not environment-friendly.
5. Premise 8: Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
6. Rule of excluded middle: Either Real Madrid or Barcelona receives more points than the other.
7. Premise 9: Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
8. Premise 10: Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
9. Conclusion: One of the teams received more points.

We can see that the conclusion follows from the premises using the rules of inference. Therefore, the conclusion "A worksheet is not biodegradable" follows from the given premises.

Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.

</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.

</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.

Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>

Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.

This means the statement must be false.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premise that all woodware is biodegradable. If a worksheet is woodware, it is biodegradable. However, if a worksheet is not woodware, it is not biodegradable. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The fourth premise states that "All paper is woodware." The conclusion is that "A worksheet is not biodegradable." The premises given are:

* All paper is woodware.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premise that all paper is woodware. If a worksheet is paper, it is biodegradable. However, if a worksheet is not paper, it is not biodegradable. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The fifth premise states that "Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing." The conclusion is that "If a worksheet is good, then it is not bad." The premises given are:

* All environment-friendly things are good.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premise that if a worksheet is good, it is not bad. If a worksheet is environment-friendly, it is good, and if it is not bad, it is not environment-friendly. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The sixth premise states that "A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly." The conclusion is that "A worksheet is not biodegradable." The premises given are:

* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premise that a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly. If a worksheet is paper, it is biodegradable, and if it is environment-friendly, it may or may not be biodegradable. However, since the conclusion states that a worksheet is not biodegradable, it must be the case that it is not environment-friendly. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The seventh premise states that "All environment-friendly things are good." The conclusion is that "If a worksheet is environment-friendly, then it is good." The premises given are:

* All environment-friendly things are good.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premise that if a worksheet is environment-friendly, it is good. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The eighth premise states that "All paper is environment-friendly." The conclusion is that "If a worksheet is paper, then it is environment-friendly." The premises given are:

* All paper is environment-friendly.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premise that if a worksheet is paper, it is environment-friendly. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The ninth premise states that "A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly." The conclusion is that "If a worksheet is paper or environment-friendly, then it is good." The premises given are:

* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
* If a worksheet is environment-friendly, then it is good.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premises that if a worksheet is paper or environment-friendly, then it is good. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

The tenth premise states that "A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly." The conclusion is that "A worksheet is not biodegradable." The premises given are:

* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
* All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.

The conclusion is reached by considering the premises that a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly, and all biodegradable things are environment-friendly. If a worksheet is paper, it is biodegradable, and if it is environment-friendly, it may or may not be biodegradable. However, since the conclusion states that a worksheet is not biodegradable, it must be the case that it is not environment-friendly. Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.

=== Example 53 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
If a person pays their taxes, then they contribute to the country.
Everyone who works for a government department pays a tax on their salary.
Everyone in the army is an employee of a government department.
Everyone convicted of murder goes to prison.
Everyone who has been to prison has a criminal record.
James was either once convicted of murder, or spent time in prison.
James either has a criminal record, or pays his taxes.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
James does not contribute to the country.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if James contributes to the country. Let's think about what we know about James. First, we know that James was either sentenced for thief or stayed in prison. However, this doesn't tell us anything about whether James contributed to the country. Second, we know that James either had a bad record in the local state or that he was respected by others. However, the premises don't tell us anything about the relationship between having a bad record and contributing to the country. Therefore, it is uncertain whether James contributes to the country.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
No songs are visuals.
All folk songs are songs.
All videos are visuals.
All movies are videos.
All sci-fi movies are movies.
Inception is a sci-fi movie.
Mac is neither a folk song nor a sci-fi movie.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Inception is a folk song.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if Inception is a folk song. We know that Inception is a sci-fi movie. Since all movies are videos and Inception is a movie, it is a video, which means it is visual. On the other hand, we know that all folk songs are songs, and no songs are visual, so no folk songs are visual. Therefore, since Inception is visual but no folk songs are visual, we know that Inception cannot be a folk song, so the statement is false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
Every chef can cook.
Some people who aren’t chefs can cook.
People who cook can make scrambled eggs and pasta.
If someone can make cookies and muffins, they are a baker.
Bakers who can also make scrambled eggs can make a good breakfast.
Luke can make cookies, scrambled eggs, and muffins, but not pasta.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Luke is a chef.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if Luke can make a good breakfast. From the last premise, we know that Luke can make cookies, scrambled eggs, and muffins. Since Luke can make cookies and muffins, they are a baker. Now, combining the information we have, since Luke is a baker and can make scrambled eggs, this means that they can make a good breakfast. Therefore, Luke can make a good breakfast, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

ETS also develops K-12 statewide assessments used for accountability testing in many states.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
ETS doesn't administer tests internationally.
</CONCLUSION>

From the given premises and conclusion, we can use the following FOL expressions:

Premises:

* All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
	+ \_\_biodegradable : x
	+ \_\_environment-friendly : y
	+ \_\_All(x) [ biodegradable(x) => environment-friendly(y) ]
* All woodware is biodegradable.
	+ \_\_woodware : x
	+ \_\_biodegradable : y
	+ \_\_All(x) [ woodware(x) => biodegradable(y) ]
* All paper is woodware.
	+ \_\_paper : x
	+ \_\_woodware : y
	+ \_\_All(x) [ paper(x) => woodware(y) ]
* Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
	+ \_\_good : x
	+ \_\_bad : x
	+ \_\_All(x) [ good(x) => bad(x) ]
* All environment-friendly things are good.
	+ \_\_good : x
	+ \_\_environment-friendly : y
	+ \_\_All(x) [ environment-friendly(y) => good(x) ]
* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
	+ \_\_paper : x
	+ \_\_environment-friendly : y
	+ \_\_workshet : z
	+ \_\_All(z) [ worksheet(z) => paper(z) ]
	+ \_\_All(z) [ worksheet(z) => environment-friendly(z) ]

Conclusion:

* A worksheet is not biodegradable.

	+ \_\_biodegradable : y
	+ \_\_All(x) [ ~worksheet(x) => ~biodegradable(x) ]

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.

</EVALUATE>

(Biodegradable(x) ∧ EnvironmentallyFriendly(x))

(Woodware(x) ∧ Biodegradable(x))

(Paper(x) ∧ Woodware(x))

(Good(x) ∧ Bad(x))

(EnvironmentallyFriendly(x) ∧ Good(x))

(Worksheet(x) ∧ (Paper(x) ∨ EnvironmentallyFriendly(x)))

(¬Biodegradable(Worksheet(x)))

The parliament cannot be held responsible for the actions of the monarch.
The monarch has a head of state role in the UK.
The UK has a Prime Minister.
The Prime Minister is the head of government in the UK.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
The parliament has a head of government role in the UK.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if the parliament has a head of government role in the UK. From the premises, we know that the parliament is responsible for making laws in the UK and that the parliament cannot be held responsible for the actions of the monarch. However, we also know that the monarch has a head of state role in the UK, and the Prime Minister is the head of government in the UK. Therefore, the parliament has no head of government role in the UK, and the conclusion is false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

The President has a head of government role in the US.

=== Example 57 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

For example, if the premise is "If it is white, then it is a snowman," and the conclusion is "It is a snowman," then we can use the modus ponens rule as follows:
"If it is white, then it is a snowman. It is white. Therefore, it is a snowman."
Similarly, if the premise is "If oils are chemicals, then chemicals are harmful," and the conclusion is "Oils are harmful," then we can use the modus ponens rule as follows:
"If oils are chemicals, then chemicals are harmful. Oils are chemicals. Therefore, oils are harmful."

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

This means the statement must be false.

</EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
Some mammals have teeth.
Platypuses have no teeth.
Platypuses are mammals.
Humans have teeth.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Platypuses are mammals with no teeth.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Generation 1:
Let's evaluate the given problem step by step:

Given Premises:

1. All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
2. All woodware is biodegradable.
3. All paper is woodware.
4. Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
5. All environment-friendly things are good.
6. A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

Conclusion:
A worksheet is not biodegradable.

First, let's evaluate the premises:

From premises 1, 2 and 3, we know that a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly. So, we can substitute "environment-friendly" with "woodware" in the conclusion.

Therefore, the conclusion becomes:
A worksheet is not biodegradable or woodware.

From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly, so the conclusion also holds for paper.

From premise 4, nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing. Therefore, a worksheet cannot be either good or bad.

From premise 5, all environment-friendly things are good. Therefore, if a worksheet is environment-friendly, then it is good. But since we already know that a worksheet cannot be good (from premise 4), this conclusion cannot hold.

From premise 6, a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly. Therefore, we cannot conclude that a worksheet is not biodegradable or woodware.

Therefore, the conclusion "A worksheet is not biodegradable" is uncertain based on the given premises.

The answer is: Uncertain.
Processed: Error

Generation 2:
The conclusion is false. Platypuses are mammals, and they have teeth. Therefore, the conclusion is false.
Processed: Error

Generation 3:
Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if the conclusion follows from the premises. The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences. The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.

1. Premise 1: All mammals have teeth.
2. Premise 2: Platypuses have no teeth.
3. Premise 3: Platypuses are mammals.
4. Premise 4: Humans have teeth.
5. Premise 5: If A is a mammal and has teeth, then A is not a platypus.
6. Premise 6: If A is a mammal and does not have teeth, then A is not a platypus.
7. Conclusion: Platypuses are mammals with no teeth.

First, we can rewrite premise 5 as: If A is a mammal and has teeth, then A is not a platypus.

Next, we can rewrite premise 6 as: If A is a mammal and does not have teeth, then A is not a platypus.

Since premise 5 and premise 6 are both about mammals with or without teeth, we can combine them into: If A is a mammal, then A has teeth.

Now, we can use the law of excluded middle to prove that the conclusion follows from the premises:

1. The law of excluded middle states that for any statement P, either P or ~P is true.
2. Premise 5 and premise 6 together state that if A is a mammal, then A has teeth.
3. Therefore, by the law of excluded middle, either A is a mammal, or ~A is a mammal.
4. If A is a mammal, then A has teeth. If ~A is a mammal, then ~A has teeth.
5. Hence, in both cases, A has teeth.

Therefore, the conclusion follows from the premises.
Processed: Error

Generation 4:
The first premise is "All biodegradable things are environment-friendly." This gives us a positive relationship between biodegradable things and environment-friendliness. The second premise is "All woodware is biodegradable." This gives us a positive relationship between woodware and biodegradability. The third premise is "All paper is woodware." This is a tautology, which states that all paper is woodware, and therefore, all paper is biodegradable. The fourth premise is "Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing." This is a contradictory statement, which cannot be true. The fifth premise is "All environment-friendly things are good." This gives us a positive relationship between environment-friendliness and goodness. The sixth premise is "A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly." This is a disjunction, which states that a worksheet can be either paper or environment-friendly. The conclusion is "A worksheet is not biodegradable." This contradicts the third premise, which states that all paper is biodegradable, and therefore, all worksheets are biodegradable. Therefore, the statement "A worksheet is not biodegradable" is false.

Generation 5:
Let's analyze the FOL expressions given for each premise and conclusion:

Premises:

1. A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
2. If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
3. Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
4. Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
5. Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.

CONCLUSION: Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.

FOL expressions:

1. ∃ x, y (La Liga soccer team(x) ∧ La Liga soccer team(y) ∧ x ≠ y) (x rankedHigherThan y if x receives more points than y in La Liga).
2. ∃ x, y (La Liga soccer team(x) ∧ La Liga soccer team(y) ∧ x ≠ y) (x rankedHigherThan y if x and y did not receive more points than each other in La Liga).
3. La Liga soccer team(Real Madrid) ∧ La Liga soccer team(Barcelona).
4. ∃ x (La Liga soccer team(x) ∧ x received more points than Barcelona in La Liga).
5. ∃ x, y (La Liga soccer team(x) ∧ La Liga soccer team(y) ∧ x did not receive more points from the games between x and y than y ∧ y did not receive more points from the games between x and y than x).

FOL expression for conclusion:

1. ∃ x, y (La Liga soccer team(x) ∧ La Liga soccer team(y) ∧ x rankedHigherThan y in La Liga).

These FOL expressions represent the given premises and conclusion in a logical and structured way, using first-order logic concepts such as quantifiers, variables, and functions. The conclusion follows logically from the premises, so the statement is true.

Generation 1:
Let's translate each of the premises and conclusion into FOL expressions:

Premises:

* All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
* All woodware is biodegradable.
* All paper is woodware.
* Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
* All environment-friendly things are good.
* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

Premise 1: ∀x (Bio(x) → Env-Friendly(x))
Premise 2: ∀x (Woodware(x) → Bio(x))
Premise 3: ∀x (Paper(x) → Woodware(x))
Premise 4: ∃x (Not-Good(x) ∧ Bad(x))
Premise 5: ∀x (Env-Friendly(x) → Good(x))
Premise 6: ∀x (Worksheet(x) → (Paper(x) ∨ Env-Friendly(x)))

Conclusion:
Worksheet(a) → ¬Bio(a)

Conclusion: ∀x (Worksheet(x) → ¬Bio(x))

Premises:

* A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
* If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
* Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
* Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
* Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.

Premise 1: ∀x,y (La Liga(x) ∧ La Liga(y) → Point(x,y) ∧ Rank(x,y))
Premise 2: ∀x, y (La Liga(x) ∧ La Liga(y) → Game(x,y) → Rank(x,y))
Premise 3: ∀x (La Liga(x) → Real Madrid(x) ∨ Barca(x))
Premise 4: ∀x (Point(Real Madrid, x) ∧ Point(Barca, x))
Premise 5: ∀x (Game(Real Madrid, x) ∧ Game(Barca, x) → ¬Point(Real Madrid, x) ∧ ¬Point(Barca, x))

Conclusion:
Real Madrid → ¬La Liga(Real Madrid)

Conclusion: ∀x (Real Madrid(x) → ¬La Liga(x))

Premises:

* All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
* All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
* No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
* All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
* Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
* If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.

Premise 1: ∀x (Professional(x) → Time(x, Sports))
Premise 2: ∀x (Olympic Gold Medal(x) → Professional(x))
Premise 3: ∀x (Time(x, Sports) → ¬Full-Time(x, Science))
Premise 4: ∀x (Nobel Physics(x) → Full-Time(x, Science))
Premise 5: ∀x (Time(x, Sports) → Amy(x))
Premise 6: ∀x (Olympic Gold Medal(x) → Amy(x))
Premise 7: ∀x (¬Nobel Physics(x) → ¬Olympic Gold Medal(x))

Conclusion:
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.

Conclusion: ∀x (¬Amy Olympic Gold Medal(x) → Amy Nobel Physics(x))

Premises:

* If a person pays their taxes, then they contribute to the country.
* Every employee of a government department pays a tax on their salary.
* Every soldier in the army is an employee of a government department.
* Every person convicted of murder goes to prison.
* Every person who has been to prison has a criminal record.
* James was either once convicted of murder, or spent time in prison.
* James either has a criminal record, or pays his taxes.
Processed: Error

Generation 2:
Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if the conclusion follows from the premises. The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences. The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.

First, we need to determine if the premises are consistent with each other. We can see that all the premises are true, so they are consistent with each other.

Next, we need to determine if the conclusion follows logically from the premises. We can see that the conclusion contradicts one of the premises, specifically premise 3. Therefore, the conclusion does not follow logically from the premises.

The answer is False.
Processed: Error

Generation 3:
Let's start by translating the premises and conclusion into FOL expressions.

Premises:

* A \_ Biodegradable \_ : A \_ Woodware \_ \_ : A \_ Paper \_ \_
* A \_ Woodware \_ \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_
* A \_ Paper \_ \_ : A \_ Dispensable \_ \_
* A \_ Good \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_
* A \_ Either \_ Paper \_ \_ \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_
* A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ \_: A \_ A \_ \_ \_
* A \_ Either \_ Paper \_ \_ \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_

Conclusion:

* A \_ Not \_ Biodegradable \_ \_

Then, we can evaluate each premise with respect to the conclusion.

1. A \_ Biodegradable \_ : A \_ Woodware \_ \_ \_
Since A \_ Woodware \_ \_ \_ \_ , and A \_ Biodegradable \_ : A \_ Woodware \_ \_ \_ , we know that A \_ Biodegradable \_ . Since A \_ Woodware \_ \_ \_ \_ and A \_ Biodegradable \_ , we also know that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ \_ . Therefore, we can conclude that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ \_ .
2. A \_ Woodware \_ \_ \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_
Since A \_ Woodware \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ , we know that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ \_ . Since A \_ Environment-friendly \_ : A \_ Good \_ , we also know that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ . Therefore, we can conclude that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ .
3. A \_ Paper \_ \_ : A \_ Dispensable \_ \_
Since A \_ Paper \_ : A \_ Woodware \_ , we know that A \_ Woodware \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ , and we also know that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ : A \_ Good \_ , so we know that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ . Since A \_ Paper \_ \_ : A \_ Dispensable \_ , we also know that A \_ Dispensable \_ \_ \_ \_ . Therefore, we can conclude that A \_ Dispensable \_ \_ \_ \_ .
4. A \_ Good \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_
Since A \_ Good \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ , we know that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ .
5. A \_ Either \_ Paper \_ \_ \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_
Since A \_ Paper \_ : A \_ Woodware \_ , we know that A \_ Woodware \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ \_ , and we also know that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ : A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ , so we know that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ . Therefore, we can conclude that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ .
6. A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ : A \_ A \_ \_ \_
Since A \_ A \_ \_ , we know that A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ , which contradicts A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ . Therefore, we cannot conclude that A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ : A \_ A \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ .
7. A \_ Either \_ Paper \_ \_ \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_
Since A \_ Paper \_ : A \_ Woodware \_ , we know that A \_ Woodware \_ : A \_ Environment-friendly \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ , and we also know that A \_ Environment-friendly \_ : A \_ Good \_ , so we know that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ . Therefore, we can conclude that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ .
8. A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ : A \_ A \_ \_ \_
Since A \_ A \_ \_ : A \_ A \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ , we know that A \_ Neither \_ A \_ \_ \_ : A \_ A \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ .

From the above, we can conclude that A \_ Good \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ \_ Generation 5:
Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.

For the first problem, we need to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions.

Premises:

* All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
* All woodware is biodegradable.
* All paper is woodware.
* Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
* All environment-friendly things are good.
* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

Conclusion:
A worksheet is not biodegradable.

We can represent the premises as follows:

* All biodegradable things are environment-friendly. (Bi(x) ∧ Fri(x))
* All woodware is biodegradable. (Wood(x) ∧ Bi(x))
* All paper is woodware. (Paper(x) ∧ Wood(x))
* Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing. (¬(G(x) ∧ B(x)) ∨ (G(x) ∧ B(x)))
* All environment-friendly things are good. (Fri(x) ∧ G(x))
* A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly. (Worksheet(x) ∨ Paper(x) ∨ Fri(x))

We can represent the conclusion as follows:

* A worksheet is not biodegradable. (¬Bi(Worksheet(x)))

Now, let's evaluate the second problem.

Premises:

* A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
* If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
* Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
* Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
* Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.

Conclusion:
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.

We can represent the premises as follows:

* If team A has more points than team B, then team A ranks higher than team B. (RankHigher(x, y) ∧ Pts(x) > Pts(y))
* If team A and team B have the same points and the points they received from the games between them are equal, then team A ranks higher than team B. (RankHigher(x, y) ∧ Pts(x) = Pts(y) ∧ PtsFromGames(x, y) = PtsFromGames(y, x))
* Real Madrid and Barcelona are La Liga soccer teams. (LaLiga(Real Madrid) ∧ LaLiga(Barcelona))
* Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. (Pts(Real Madrid) > Pts(Barcelona))
* Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them. (PtsFromGames(Real Madrid, Barcelona) = PtsFromGames(Barcelona, Real Madrid))

We can represent the conclusion as follows:

* Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. (RankHigher(Real Madrid, Barcelona))

Finally, let's evaluate the third problem.

Premises:

* All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
* All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
* No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
* All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
* Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
* If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.

Conclusion:
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate.

We can represent the premises as follows:

* All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports. (ProfessionalAthlete(x) ∧ SpendsMostTimeOnSports(x))
* All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes. (OlympicGold(x) ∧ ProfessionalAthlete(x))
* No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports. (Scientist(x) ∧ NotSpentMostTimeOnSports(x))
* All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists. (NobelPhysics(x) ∧ Scientist(x))
Processed: Error

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

Let's evaluate the problem step by step:

<PREMISES>
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions
</PREMISES>

For this problem, we need to determine whether the conclusion "A worksheet is not biodegradable" follows from the premises. The premises are given as a set of FOL sentences, and the conclusion is given as a single FOL sentence.

We need to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions. This can be done by assigning variables and using logical operators to represent the relationships between the entities in the domain of the problem.

Let's consider each of the premises and conclusions in turn:

<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>

First, we can represent the entities in the domain of the problem using variables:

* Let "B" be the category of biodegradable things.
* Let "W" be the category of woodware.
* Let "P" be the category of paper.
* Let "G" be the category of good things.
* Let "E" be the category of environment-friendly things.
* Let "F" be the category of friendly things.
* Let "W" be the category of worksheets.

Next, we can use logical operators to represent the relationships between the entities:

* B ∩ W = P: All woodware is paper.
* B ∩ W ∩ E = W: All biodegradable things are woodware.
* P ∩ W = W: All paper is woodware.
* G ∩ F = G: All good things are friendly things.
* E ∩ F = G: All environment-friendly things are good.
* W ∩ E = W or W ∩ P: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

Finally, we can formulate the conclusion in FOL:

* ¬(W ∩ E): A worksheet is not biodegradable.

Note that the negation symbol "¬" means "not", and it is used to negate the conclusion.

<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>

We can now evaluate the problem using the premises and conclusion in FOL:

<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not biodegradable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensable or not, so the statement is uncertain.

ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

The conclusion "A worksheet is not biodegradable" follows from the premises given in the FOL expressions:

* B ∩ W = P: All woodware is paper.
* P ∩ W = W: All paper is woodware.
* W ∩ E = W or W ∩ P: A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.

Therefore, the conclusion is true.

ANSWER:	True
Processed: Uncertain

=== Example 66 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>

Everyone who works for a government department pays a tax on their salary.
Everyone in the army is an employee of a government department.

Everyone who has been to prison has a criminal record.
James was either once convicted of murder, or spent time in prison.
James either has a criminal record, or pays his taxes.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
James does not contribute to the country.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

First, we know that James was either sentenced for thief or stayed in prison. However, this doesn't tell us anything about whether James contributed to the country. Second, we know that James either had a bad record in the local state or that he was respected by others. However, the premises don't tell us anything about the relationship between having a bad record and contributing to the country. Therefore, it is uncertain whether James contributes to the country.

On the other hand, we know that all folk songs are songs, and no songs are visual, so no folk songs are visual. </EVALUATE>

The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

The first premise is "All biodegradable things are environment-friendly." The conclusion is that "A worksheet is not biodegradable."

To evaluate this argument, we need to consider each premise and the conclusion one by one. Let's start with the first premise: "All biodegradable things are environment-friendly." This statement can be represented in FOL as:

(∀x)(Biodegradable(x) → Environment-friendly(x))

Now let's look at the second premise: "All woodware is biodegradable." This can be represented in FOL as:

(∀x)(Woodware(x) → Biodegradable(x))

The third premise is "All paper is woodware." This can be represented as:

(∀x)(Paper(x) → Woodware(x))

The fourth premise states that "Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing." This can be represented in FOL as:

(∃ x) (Good(x) ∧ Bad(x))

The fifth premise is that "All environment-friendly things are good." This can be represented in FOL as:

(∀x)(Environment-friendly(x) → Good(x))

The sixth premise states that a worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly. This can be represented in FOL as:

(∃x)(Worksheet(x) → (Paper(x) ∨ Environment-friendly(x)))

Now we can evaluate the conclusion using these premises. Since a worksheet is paper and paper is biodegradable, the worksheet is biodegradable. However, we don't know if the worksheet is environment-friendly. Since environment-friendly things are good, if the worksheet is environment-friendly, it would be good. But we don't know this. Therefore, we cannot determine if a worksheet is not biodegradable based on these premises. The argument is uncertain.

Therefore, the conclusion is True.

=== Example 69 ===
Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
If a person pays their taxes, then they contribute to the country.
Everyone who works for a government department pays a tax on their salary.
Everyone in the army is an employee of a government department.
Everyone convicted of murder goes to prison.
Everyone who has been to prison has a criminal record.
James was either once convicted of murder, or spent time in prison.
James either has a criminal record, or pays his taxes.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
James does not contribute to the country.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if James contributes to the country. Let's think about what we know about James. First, we know that James was either sentenced for thief or stayed in prison. However, this doesn't tell us anything about whether James contributed to the country. Second, we know that James either had a bad record in the local state or that he was respected by others. However, the premises don't tell us anything about the relationship between having a bad record and contributing to the country. Therefore, it is uncertain whether James contributes to the country.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
No songs are visuals.
All folk songs are songs.
All videos are visuals.
All movies are videos.
All sci-fi movies are movies.
Inception is a sci-fi movie.
Mac is neither a folk song nor a sci-fi movie.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Inception is a folk song.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if Inception is a folk song. We know that Inception is a sci-fi movie. Since all movies are videos and Inception is a movie, it is a video, which means it is visual. On the other hand, we know that all folk songs are songs, and no songs are visual, so no folk songs are visual. Therefore, since Inception is visual but no folk songs are visual, we know that Inception cannot be a folk song, so the statement is false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
Every chef can cook.
Some people who aren’t chefs can cook.
People who cook can make scrambled eggs and pasta.
If someone can make cookies and muffins, they are a baker.
Bakers who can also make scrambled eggs can make a good breakfast.
Luke can make cookies, scrambled eggs, and muffins, but not pasta.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Luke is a chef.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if Luke can make a good breakfast. From the last premise, we know that Luke can make cookies, scrambled eggs, and muffins. Since Luke can make cookies and muffins, they are a baker. Now, combining the information we have, since Luke is a baker and can make scrambled eggs, this means that they can make a good breakfast. Therefore, Luke can make a good breakfast, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

ETS doesn't administer tests internationally.

Therefore, both parts of the conclusion are true, and the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

(∃x)(Biodegradable(x) → Environment-friendly(x))

Next, we have the premise "All woodware is biodegradable." We can translate this into FOL as:

(∃x)(Woodware(x) → Biodegradable(x))

Finally, we have the premise "All paper is woodware." We can translate this into FOL as:

(∃x)(Paper(x) → Woodware(x))

The conclusion is given as "A worksheet is not biodegradable." We can translate this into FOL as:

(∃x)(Worksheet(x) → ¬Biodegradable(x))

Now let's evaluate the conclusion. From the premises, we know that all woodware is biodegradable and all paper is woodware. Therefore, we can conclude that all worksheets are biodegradable. So the conclusion is false, and the statement is uncertain.

Therefore, the answer is Uncertain.

Prompt:
The following is a first-order logic (FOL) problem.
The problem is to determine whether the conclusion follows from the premises.
The premises are given in the form of a set of first-order logic sentences.
The conclusion is given in the form of a single first-order logic sentence.
The task is to translate each of the premises and conclusions into FOL expressions 


<PREMISES>
All biodegradable things are environment-friendly.
All woodware is biodegradable.
All paper is woodware.
Nothing is a good thing and also a bad thing.
All environment-friendly things are good.
A worksheet is either paper or environment-friendly.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
A worksheet is not biodegradable.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if a worksheet is not dispensable. From premise 6, we know that a worksheet is either paper or is environment-friendly. If it is paper, then from premise 3, a worksheet is woodware, and from premise 2, a worksheet is dispensable. If it is environment-friendly, we know it is good from premise 5, but we know nothing about whether it is dispensable. Therefore, we don't know if a worksheet is dispensible or not, so the statement is uncertain.
ANSWER:	Uncertain
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
A La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another La Liga soccer team if it receives more points.
If there are two La Liga soccer teams and neither has more points than the other, then the team which receives more points from the games between the two teams ranks higher.
Real Madrid and Barcelona are both La Liga soccer teams.
Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona.
Neither Real Madrid nor Barcelona received more points from the games between them.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate if in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona. From premise 1, we know that a La Liga soccer team ranks higher than another if it receives more points. From premise 4, we know that in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona. Therefore, in La Liga 2021-2022, Real Madrid received more points than Barcelona, so Real Madrid ranks higher than Barcelona, so the statement is true.
ANSWER:	True
</EVALUATE>

<PREMISES>
All professional athletes spend most of their time on sports.
All Olympic gold medal winners are professional athletes.
No full-time scientists spend the majority of their time on sports.
All Nobel physics laureates are full-time scientists.
Amy spends the most time on sports, or Amy is an Olympic gold medal winner.
If Amy is not a Nobel physics laureate, then Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner.
</PREMISES>
<CONCLUSION>
If Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel physics laureate.
</CONCLUSION>
<EVALUATE>

Let's think step by step. We want to evaluate the statement "if Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner, then Amy is a Nobel laureate". Let's assume that Amy is not an Olympic gold medal winner. This doesn't tell us anything about whether Amy is a Nobel laureate, so the statement isn't true, meaning it is either False or Uncertain. To distinguish between the two, notice that we could have a scenario where Amy is neither an Olympic gold medal winner nor a Nobel laureate. None of the premises are violated in this case. This means the statement must be false.
ANSWER:	False
</EVALUATE>
